This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.CL (Computation and Language) as it deals with text representation using LSTM models. Additionally, the paper also mentions classification and sequence labeling benchmarks, which are common tasks in natural language processing. 

The paper could also belong to cs.LG (Machine Learning) as it proposes a new LSTM structure for text representation, which could be of interest to researchers working on machine learning models for natural language processing. 

cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) is another likely sub-category as the paper proposes a novel approach for encoding text, which could be useful for various AI applications such as chatbots, sentiment analysis, and text classification. 

cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) is also a possible sub-category as the paper deals with neural network models, specifically LSTM models, for text representation. 

Finally, cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) is a less likely sub-category, but still possible as the paper mentions using LSTM models for sequence labeling tasks, which could be relevant to computer vision applications such as object detection and tracking.
